lave narratives from the abolitionist era. Linking the racialized discourses of slavery and Romanticism, it boldly calls for a reconfiguration of U.S. and British Romanticism that places slavery at its center. Impossible Witnesses addresses some of the major literary figures and representations of slavery in light of discourses on natural rights and law, offers an account of Foucauldian discourse analysis as it applies to the problem of "bearing witness," and analyzes specific narratives such as "Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass," and "The Interesting Narrative of the Life of Olaudah Equiano." A work of great depth and originality, Impossible Witnesses renders traditional interpretations of Romanticism impossible and places Dwight A. McBride at the forefront of studies in race and literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistory and criticismvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aAmerican prose literaturezUnited StatesxAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticismy19th century. 0aAmerican prose literaturezUnited StatesxHistory and criticismy19th century. 0aAntislavery movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aAutobiographyxAfrican American authors. 0aSlavery in literature. 0aSlavesxHistory and criticismvBiography. 0aSlavesxIntellectual life. 0aSlaves' writings, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081475604140uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814759738.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759738423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814759738/original  a9